  "doc_id": "18134",
  "text": "Several early researchers made significant progress in the field of MCS, laying the groundwork for modern total artificial hearts (TAHs) and VADs. In 1963, Liotta et al. [CITATION_1] reported the successful use of an implantable artificial ventricle in a patient who was in cardiogenic shock after a valve replacement procedure. Several years later, DeBakey [CITATION_2] utilized a pneumatically driven VAD to bridge a young woman to myocardial recovery after cardiac surgery. The development and success of these MCS devices fueled the hope that such systems could be used to treat not only postcardiotomy cardiogenic shock but also HF.",
